data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code in EF Core 10. Here's each one:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now accepts a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` code **won't compile** because EF 10 added a `Func<>` overload that takes priority over the `Expression<Func<>>` one. The fix is dramatically simpler:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 — no expression trees needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

Delete all the `Expression.Parameter` / `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two sub-changes

**a) Column uniquification:** If `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously mapped to the same `Street` column, EF 10 will auto-uniquify them (e.g. `Street` and `Street1`). To keep existing schema, pin the names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested full-path naming:** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`. EF 10 now uses `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve existing column names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> ⚠️ Both of these will generate migrations that rename/add columns if you don't pin names. Run `dotnet ef migrations add` after upgrading and inspect carefully.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

This applies to `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, `CommandScalarExecuted`, and all other methods on the interface as well.
